<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos viscida </i>is a long-lived, evergreen, sclerophyllous shrub that grows up to 4 m; its white glaucous leaves are ovate to elliptic. Plants lack a lignotuber. Shrubs produce abundant seed after they are 10 years old that collects in a seed bank in the duff and soil. Plants can reproduce by layering as well (Howard 1992h). <br/>
<br/>
In the many portions of its range, stands of <i>A. viscida </i>are transitional to montane forests or woodland types. Other stands persist for over 100 years. <i>A. viscida </i>grows under a wide range of conditions as a result of the species’s high ecological plasticity. Three subspecies are recognized in the <i>Jepson Manual </i>(ssp. <i>mariposa, </i>ssp. <i>pulchella, </i>ssp. <i>viscida</i>), and hybrids with <i>A. canescens </i>and <i>A. patula </i>are known. Ssp. <i>mariposa </i>grows in the central and southern Sierra Nevada; ssp. <i>pulchella </i>grows in the Klamath Mountains and North Coast Ranges; and ssp. <i>viscida </i>grows in the Cascades, Klamath Mountains, and Sierra Nevada. Ssp. <i>pulchella </i>regularly forms stands on serpentine Colusa, Glenn, Mendocino, Napa, and Tehama Cos. Alexander et al. (2007) recognized it as a separate alliance endemic to serpentine. However, since sampling has been minimal in the range of the species, we take a conservative view and include all forms of <i>A. viscida </i>in this alliance at this time. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
