<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Arctostaphylos viscida </i>is an obligate seeder. Seeds germinate after cold stratification in winter followed by heat scarification from fire. Seedling establishment is often high. Developing stands become dense within the first 5 years. <i>A. viscida </i>is adapted to high-intensity, long-interval fires. Open stands on ridgetops or on serpentine substrates have relatively low fire return rates. Dense montane stands have fire return rates of about 50 years (Howard 1992h).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (20-70+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Seasonality</td>
			<td>Late summer-fall
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Size/extent</td>
			<td>Medium to large—up to and beyond stand
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Complexity</td>
			<td>Low to moderate
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Intensity</td>
			<td>High
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
