	</table>
</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac, Ae-r, At-u). Stands occur throughout the section; they are most extensive in the eastern portions, commonly occurring on ultramafic substrates. Stands cover large portions of the upper Sacramento River watershed around Lake Shasta. These stands followed restoration projects in the 1940s after the copper smelters were closed in the Iron Mountain area (Sawyer 2006). Stands are also extensive around Whiskeytown Lake (Lee 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba, Bc-f). The species is found throughout most of the section; it forms stands in the southern portions on serpentine, mostly on south-facing slopes. In Napa Co., stands with a strong component of ssp. <i>pulchella</i> were mapped as a mixture of alliances (the <i>Quercus durata-Arctostaphylos viscida-Adenostoma fasciculata</i> xeric serpentine chaparral mapping unit) in over 1350 stands covering 10,900 ha. (Thorne et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-b). Stands commonly occur with other chaparral types in the eastern foothills of the Yolla Bolly Mountains both on and off serpentine. Stands are described for Frenzel Creek RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1983, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ef-g, Ep). Stands occur adjacent to conifer forests and evergreen hardwoods, and with several chaparral types at lower elevations in the western portion of the section (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b). The similar-looking <i>Arctostaphylos mewukka</i> co-occurs with <i>A. viscida</i> in the central Sierra Nevada. Unlike <i>A. viscida, A. mewukka</i> has a lignotuber, suggesting a different fire regime. Inventorying and mapping of <i>A. mewukka</i> stands need to be done.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-d). Stands occur adjacent to woodland types on volcanic mudflows and on gabbro in the Pine Hill area (Hunter and Horenstein 1992), on deep Miocene clays at Apricum Hill Ecological Reserve (Wood and Parker 1988), and in Big Grizzly Mountain RNA (Cheng 2004). Stands in the Pine Hill area occur with <i>Salvia sonomensis</i> (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dc, Df-g, Dj, Dl). The species and stands are common in the section at lower montane elevations. Stands are conspicuous around Shasta Valley and in the Shingletown area.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Managers have used fire to convert obligate-seeding manzanita brush fields to forests and grassland because repeated, short-interval fires deplete the seed bank. <i>Arctostaphylos viscida </i>inhibits the growth of conifer seedlings allelopathically (Tinnin and Kirkpatrick 1985). Clearing <i>A. viscida </i>shrubs increases the success of <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii </i>plantings (Amaranthus et al. 1990). Stands are long lasting, even on productive soils, but in time are invaded by conifers as the shrub canopy opens up (Buchanan et al. 1966, Minore et al. 1988). </div>
</div>

    

    

